## "Destination: Skaro" – A Fleeting Glimpse of Origins

"Destination: Skaro," a rather melodramatic title for what amounts to a five-minute whisper in the grand tapestry of [Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who), is officially designated as a [Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who) charity special. It aired on the 17th of November, 2023, a date etched into the annals of [Children in Need](/Children_in_Need) programming. This brief excursion, however, marked a significant, albeit brief, return for [David Tennant](/David_Tennant) as the [Fourteenth Doctor](/Fourteenth_Doctor), preceding the more substantial fare of the [Doctor Who specials (2023)](/Doctor_Who_specials_(2023)) celebrating the show's sixtieth anniversary. The premise, for what it's worth, plunges a newly [regenerated](/Regeneration_(Doctor_Who)) [Doctor](/The_Doctor_(Doctor_Who)) into the heart of [Skaro](/Skaro) at precisely the wrong, or perhaps entirely the right, moment: the genesis of the [Daleks](/Dalek), under the watchful, malevolent gaze of [Davros](/Davros). Penned by the ever-present [Russell T Davies](/Russell_T_Davies), the current [showrunner](/Showrunner), and steered by the direction of [Jamie Donoughue](/Jamie_Donoughue), this mini-episode managed to garner favorable reviews, though not without stirring the pot of fan discontent regarding certain creative choices concerning Davros.

### Cast

The limited roster of this particular adventure featured:

*   **[David Tennant](/David_Tennant)** as the [Fourteenth Doctor](/Fourteenth_Doctor) – Yes, *that* Doctor. Apparently, he couldn't quite stay away, even for a five-minute cameo. One might wonder if he just stumbled in, or if there's a deeper, more inconvenient reason for his presence.
*   **[Julian Bleach](/Julian_Bleach)** as [Davros](/Davros) – A familiar face for those who've had the displeasure of witnessing Davros's machinations before. Bleach, bless his theatrical heart, seems to revel in the role of cosmic villainy.
*   **[Nicholas Briggs](/Nicholas_Briggs)** – The ubiquitous voice of the [Dalek](/Dalek). A man whose vocal cords have been responsible for more existential dread than a philosophy lecture on a Monday.
*   **[Barnaby Edwards](/Barnaby_Edwards)** – The physical presence behind the Dalek. One assumes this involves a great deal of maneuvering and possibly a lingering scent of ozone.
*   **[Mawaan Rizwan](/Mawaan_Rizwan)** – Portraying Mr. Castavillian. A character whose primary function seems to be serving as a sounding board for Davros's ego and a convenient witness to temporal chaos.

### Production

The architects of this brief spectacle were:

*   **Directed by [Jamie Donoughue](/Jamie_Donoughue)** – He managed to wrangle Tennant, a Dalek, and the very fabric of time into a coherent, albeit short, narrative. Impressive, I suppose, if you're into that sort of thing.
*   **Written by [Russell T Davies](/Russell_T_Davies)** – The man who seems to have a permanent residency in the [Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who) writing room. He’s responsible for the show's resurgence, its various iterations, and now, apparently, its five-minute detours.
*   **Produced by Vicky Delow and [Scott Handcock](/Scott_Handcock)** – The unsung heroes who ensure the cameras roll and the props don't spontaneously combust.
*   **Executive Producer: Russell T Davies** – Yes, he’s everywhere. Like a particularly persistent rumour.

This mini-episode, "Destination: Skaro," is chronologically nestled after the [Fourteenth Doctor](/Fourteenth_Doctor)'s appearance in the comic *Liberation of the Daleks*. It functions as an indirect [prequel](/Prequel) to the seminal 1975 serial, [Genesis of the Daleks](/Genesis_of_the_Daleks). More importantly, it served as a rather abrupt bridge between the conclusion of Jodie Whittaker's era in "[The Power of the Doctor](/The_Power_of_the_Doctor)" and the commencement of the new era with "[The Star Beast](/The_Star_Beast_(Doctor_Who_episode))".

The decision to present [Davros](/Davros) as [able-bodied](/Able-bodied) was a deliberate departure from his established, often wheelchair-bound, persona. [Russell T Davies](/Russell_T_Davies) himself explained this as a conscious rejection of the tired trope that associates physical disability with villainy. He argued that in a world that is evolving, [Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who) must reflect that change, especially during a broadcast aimed at [Children in Need](/Children_in_Need), a time when conversations around disability and difference are paramount. Davies stated, "There's a problem with the Davros of old, in that he's a wheelchair user who is evil. There's a long tradition of associating disability with evil but time, society, culture and taste has moved on. When the world changes, Doctor Who has to change as well. Especially on Children in Need night, when issues of disability and otherness come right to the front of the conversation." A noble sentiment, though one that clearly ruffled a few feathers among the purists.

Furthermore, the episode provided a canonical, and frankly rather amusing, explanation for the Daleks' iconic [plunger](/Plunger)-like appendages. [Jamie Donoughue](/Jamie_Donoughue)'s direction was executed at [Bad Wolf Studios](/Bad_Wolf_(production_company)) in [Cardiff, Wales](/Cardiff,_Wales), with filming taking place on April 18, 2023, a period when the fourteenth series was still very much in its nascent stages. The Dalek prop itself was a veteran, having journeyed all the way from [Glasgow](/Glasgow).

[David Tennant](/David_Tennant)'s return as the Fourteenth Doctor was his second televised appearance in this guise, following a brief, almost spectral, cameo in "The Power of the Doctor." It's a peculiar thing, this insistence on revisiting familiar faces. Tennant apparently filmed his scenes on his birthday, a detail that the production team no doubt celebrated with forced jollity. [Mawaan Rizwan](/Mawaan_Rizwan) played his part as Mr. Castavillian with what one presumes was appropriate bewilderment. [Julian Bleach](/Julian_Bleach), a seasoned veteran of Davros portrayals, reprised his role, having previously inhabited the character in 2008 and 2015. [Barnaby Edwards](/Barnaby_Edwards) returned to operate the Dalek, a task surely requiring a certain level of stoicism, while [Nicholas Briggs](/Nicholas_Briggs) lent his distinctive voice to the creature. Briggs also provided the voice of Nyder, a character originally played by the late [Peter Miles](/Peter_Miles_(English_actor)) in [Genesis of the Daleks](/Genesis_of_the_Daleks), heard fleetingly through a speaker.

### Plot

On the desolate plains of [Skaro](/Skaro), [Davros](/Davros) unfurled his latest masterpiece to a suitably impressed Mr. Castavillian. This was no mere gadget; it was hailed as the "travel machine," the supposed pinnacle of [Kaled](/Kaled) evolution. Castavillian, eager to impress, tossed around names for this marvel, all of them anagrams of "Kaled." Davros, predictably, found them all wanting. His brief absence from the scene was all the invitation the universe, or rather, the [TARDIS](/TARDIS), needed.

Mere minutes – sixty, to be precise – after a rather jarring [regeneration](/Regeneration_(Doctor_Who)), the [Doctor](/The_Doctor_(Doctor_Who)) crash-landed, with all the grace of a falling asteroid, directly into Davros's nascent creation, reducing a significant portion of it to scrap. The Doctor, sporting his familiar, yet somehow *new*, face, initially expressed confusion to Castavillian about the unexpected return of his previous visage. This bewilderment quickly morphed into dawning horror as he recognized the mangled remains of his accidental target: a [Dalek](/Dalek).

Castavillian, ever the opportunist, scribbled down "Dalek" as the Doctor uttered it, a name born from destruction. The Doctor, realizing the gravity of his temporal faux pas – landing precisely at the moment the Daleks were being conceived – offered a rather unhelpful gesture by handing Castavillian a [plunger](/Plunger) to replace the damaged appendage on the proto-Dalek. With a sigh that suggested the weight of infinite timelines pressing down, the Doctor departed, just as Davros made his grand return. Davros, upon surveying the damaged, yet somehow *improved*, creation, gave a subtle nod of approval. The changes were accepted. The universe, it seemed, was already on its inevitable collision course.

### Release

**Broadcast**

"Destination: Skaro" was unleashed upon the unsuspecting public on [BBC One](/BBC_One) on November 17, 2023, as part of the annual [Children in Need](/Children_in_Need) telethon. It was accompanied by an episode of [Doctor Who: Unleashed](/Doctor_Who:_Unleashed), presumably to dissect the profound implications of a five-minute skit. The entirety of the [Children in Need](/Children_in_Need) special drew in a respectable 3.77 million viewers, a testament to the enduring, if sometimes perplexing, appeal of the show.

For those who prefer their temporal narratives bound in paper, a [novelisation](/Novelisation) by [Steve Cole](/Stephen_Cole_(writer)) was released on September 5, 2024, as part of *The Official Annual 2025*. A further iteration appeared on September 19, 2024, within *Fifteen Doctors 15 Stories*, specifically within the Fourteenth Doctor's collection, "Fleeting Faces."

### Critical Response

The reception to "Destination: Skaro" was, predictably, a mixed bag. Adi Tantimedh, writing for [Bleeding Cool](/Bleeding_Cool), awarded the special a perfect 10/10, declaring it the antidote to the perceived creative stagnation under former showrunner [Chris Chibnall](/Chris_Chibnall). He lauded its "consistently surprising and hilarious" nature and proclaimed it a "masterclass in storytelling and comedy acting."

Jack Trestrail of Nerdgazm offered praise for [David Tennant](/David_Tennant)'s performance, describing him as "energised as ever" and calling the special "a real breath of fresh air after 13 months off the air." Trestrail also noted a subtle shift in Tennant's portrayal of the Fourteenth Doctor compared to the [Tenth Doctor](/Tenth_Doctor), finding the former to be "more human, and much less filled with rage."

However, the mini-episode was not without its detractors. The controversial decision to portray [Davros](/Davros) as physically able-bodied ignited a firestorm among a segment of the fanbase, leading to criticism and debate. This [retroactive](/Retroactive_continuity) alteration to a long-established character trait proved to be a sticking point for many, overshadowing the narrative itself for some.

